I'm going to introduce you to some vastly different writing... this is from some earlier work... I was 30 when I wrote this.. for now I am 47... so there has been growth... take a look and provide me an analysis:

‚ÄúJulie, Julie, Julie.  She‚Äôs gorgeous.‚Äù

I blinked.  ‚ÄúJulie who?‚Äù  It was the first time I‚Äôd ever heard Robert mention a specific girl by name, so I was a bit curious.

‚ÄúOh, you don‚Äôt know her.  She‚Äôs just my new girlfriend,‚Äù Robert said casually, as though he‚Äôd had dozens of girlfriends.

‚ÄúYou?  Girlfriend?  Do you even know what a girl is?‚Äù

‚ÄúShe‚Äôs in my English class.  And yes I do.  She is beautiful.‚Äù

Robert and I had a strange friendship.  He was an only child, and was a rival with everyone.  When he moved to town, he had set up a computer Bulletin Board System on his Commodore 64, which was a few years out of date compared to the other boards in town.  Bulletin Board Systems, or ‚Äúboards‚Äù as we called them, were popular among computer geeks in the 80s and early 90s, back before anyone knew what the Internet was.  They were just personal computers connected to telephone lines that allowed people dial in and exchange email, play games, and download files.  They often had running themes.  Pornography themed boards were particularly popular.  Robert and I were both into computers.  We were both programmers.  And we both ran Bulletin Board Systems.  He was also opinionated, cocky, and fiercely competitive.  Yes, you could say that I liked...  no, tolerated him from the very beginning.

‚ÄúIt‚Äôs your turn.‚Äù  I tapped the phone receiver.  ‚ÄúYou there?‚Äù

‚ÄúOh, sorry.‚Äù  Key clicks echoed over the phone.  My computer screen flickered.  ‚ÄúYour move.‚Äù

We met after I logging onto his board during the summer.  It was a rather odd experience.  Ten minutes after I typed in my contact information, he broke into chat to say hello, and the next thing I knew, he had invited himself over for dinner.  He was a year behind me in school, and had a year to go before he started high school.  I doubted he had many real friends.  Nobody I knew seemed to like him, including my folks.  It was even more doubtful that he had a girlfriend.  Of course, I had been in a steady long-distance relationship for almost two years.  I knew everything there was to know about women!

‚ÄúI know everything there is to know about women!‚Äù I said confidently, ‚ÄúIf you ever need any tips, just let me know.‚Äù  Click.  ‚ÄúWhat was her name again?‚Äù

‚ÄúJulie.  My girlfriend‚Äôs name is Julie.‚Äù

Suspicious.  I knew him pretty well by then.  We had talked on the phone almost every day for months, tying up our parents main house line; mostly trying to one-up each other with computer knowledge as we hacked away on our machines.  He wasn‚Äôt the type to have a girlfriend.  In fact, he was exactly the type who would invent an entire relationship with a girl he never met.  He was probably infatuated with someone.  Chances were good that if she even existed, he probably hadn‚Äôt introduced himself yet.  He had likely dreamed up some elaborate Hollywood romance in his head.  But why was he telling me this?  Did he want to make me jealous?  Was he trying to beat me at something?

‚ÄúYou can‚Äôt beat me, dude.‚Äù  I said dismissively.  ‚ÄúI‚Äôve got your queen.‚Äù  I didn‚Äôt know why I bothered.  Every time I won, I was a cheater, and every time I lost, I was a loser.  It was always lose-lose with him.

‚ÄúA necessary sacrifice.‚Äù  He always had a deluded sense of accomplishment.  Key clicks continued to echo over the phone.  A long pause...  click.  My screen updated.

‚ÄúBad move,‚Äù I said.  Click, click.  ‚ÄúYou sure you wanted to do that?‚Äù

‚ÄúYou know, you really suck at this game, and I‚Äôm about to put you in check.  Your turn!‚Äù

I sighed.  Click.  ‚ÄúCheckmate.‚Äù

---

A few days passed.  Click, click.  Click, click.  ‚ÄúBad move,‚Äù I thought.  Click, click.  ‚ÄúArrogant prick.‚Äù  Click, click.  ‚ÄúAlways accuses me of cheating.‚Äù  Click, click.  ‚ÄúNever gives credit.‚Äù  Click, click.  ‚ÄúNo respect.‚Äù  Click, click.  ‚ÄúNo satisfaction.‚Äù  Click.

There had to be a way to bust him down a notch.

---

An idea sparked.  Coincidentally, I had a friend named Julie.  Wondering if she would be interested in helping me play a cruel childish prank, I called her up.  After a little persuasion, she agreed.

Ring, ring.  ‚ÄúHello?‚Äù

‚ÄúRobert?‚Äù

‚ÄúYeah?‚Äù

‚ÄúThis is Julie.‚Äù

‚ÄúJulie?‚Äù

‚ÄúYou know, from school?‚Äù

‚ÄúOh, Julie!  Hi!  I didn‚Äôt know you had my number.‚Äù

