This is something more recent.. it's not "Current" for it was written in 2015...  but here it is:

Bitbumped

	‚ÄúPlease, put down the gun, sir!‚Äù The police captain exhibited a certain well rehearsed command in his voice, as if he had said it a thousand times‚Äîwhich I'm sure he had, after all‚Äîduring his thirty-five years on the force. But this time, it was different. This time, he wasn't in control. I'd obviously caught him off guard.
	‚ÄúThe bad guys must be really responsive to that request. Bet it's served you well over the years.‚Äù A few moments of awkward silence pass. I already had him on his stomach, disarmed, with his hands behind his back, zip-tied‚Äîa position he was obviously familiar with, but not a position he was accustomed to assuming himself. I'm sure he was already thinking of ways to disarm me. Sometimes, for a few moments, I'm tempted to let them do it, just to add a little more excitement to the evening. But I never do. ‚ÄúThat's odd, you said those same words earlier, and nothing happened. I wonder why I'm not putting the gun down?‚Äù At this point, I always look at my gun with a puzzled look on my face, half expecting a laugh from... someone. Nope. Nothing. Once again, I sigh, and after a few moments, I force out a chuckle, if anything, in order to break up the silent awkwardness. ‚ÄúI'll tell you what I'm going to do. Since you asked so nicely, I'm going to put down the gun. But first, you have to do something for me? Can you do something for me first, Dave?‚Äù
	‚ÄúWait... wait a minute! My name isn't Dave! There must be some misunderstanding. You've obviously got the wrong guy!‚Äù	
	I was toying with him, of course. I call them all Dave. Even the women. This time Dave's real name was Richard Dawson.
	Richard. I almost chuckle at the thought and wonder why it hadn't occurred to me before. The name Richard, that is. Maybe I should start calling them all Dick. No, no. Just need to call them Dave. Dave is a perfectly suitable name for any marked man.
	I had done my homework. Enough to get the job done anyway. He was fifty-seven. Married twice; divorced twice. Father of four grown children. Five if you count a one night stand at his first bachelor party in Vegas thirty years ago. That marriage was doomed from the beginning. And the kid? I'm almost positive he doesn't know he exists. He does spend time with his grandkids though. Family, no matter how screwed up, is always important during these moments. The rest of life becomes background noise. In the end, if they have family, a healthy dose of facing your own mortality helps to realign perceptions.
	‚ÄúYou know what Dave, it takes a lot of nerve to come into a man's home and hold a gun to his head. And someone of your importance? Someone of your stature in the community? Well, that would take cast iron balls, wouldn't it? As I am sure you understand, holding a gun in my hand and pointing it at your head gives me certain advantages that I otherwise would not have if I were to put it down as you have so politely asked. I'm sure that as a sworn officer of the law, you've been trained to sympathize with this situation. You're obviously trained to use deadly force. And there's a good reason for that. But, I wonder what you are trained to do if I were to... shoot off your cock and balls.‚Äù I lower the gun and shove it just under his ass and in between his legs, targeting the most likely culprits responsible for what is‚Äînine times out of ten‚Äîthe primary reason I was hired to do this job in the first place. ‚ÄúI'll bet you twenty bucks that I can get it all off in one shot.‚Äù
	‚ÄúW-w-wait... wait a minute! I told you, my name isn't Dave! What is it you want from me? Please put away the gun! Just tell me what you fucking want me to do!‚Äù
	‚ÄúWell, Dave. It's been a really long time since I've seen a grown man piss his pants.‚Äù
	‚ÄúOh, come on! You're fucking joking, you crazy sack of shit!‚Äù
	I try to look surprised at this point. I should have asked him to do the Irish Jig or maybe sing me Happy Birthday. I actually did that once‚Äîhave Dave sing me Happy Birthday. Of course, on that particular day, it really was my birthday. Sadly, that day wasn't today. This guy was obviously too proud to piss himself, even with a gun to his head. ‚ÄúYou know, when I was a kid, my mother always told me I should become a comedian, and I tried it for a few years, but it just didn't pay the rent. Maybe it's because I'm only half Jewish.‚Äù
	‚ÄúFucking crazy-ass cocksucker! Did Morison hire you!?‚Äù
	‚ÄúA man like you has plenty of enemies, I'm sure. I'm so glad you've made this deduction already. Really, I am. It saves me from explaining things in unnecessary detail before we conduct our final business. But honestly, I have no idea who hired me. After all, this is the Information Age, Dave. It would seem that over the last few years while you've been busy refining the finer points on good old fashion police work, some egghead at MIT came up with everything anybody needs in order to bitbump you out of existence. Don't ask me how it all works, I only know that I won the lowest bid on your contract. But honestly, Dave, you should have learned to keep your head down and stop pissing people off.‚Äù
	At this point, I half hope that they don't offer me money. They always offer me money.
	‚ÄúGod dammit man! What the fuck are you talking about!? What the hell does MIT have to do with me?! Look! Whatever they are offering you, I'll double it!‚Äù
	So predictable. Again with the money. This is so disappointing, because it's so damn unprofessional. I have a five star rating on my profile for a reason. If I get even one negative review, I'll miss out on the exclusive five star contracts. Most of the time, I get six figures for a five star exclusive. But regular contracts? Fuck that‚ÄîI'm not working my way up through the system again; too much work. I'd rather live in poverty than grind through the bargain basement cheating spouse track again. Fucking low hanging fruit grabbing assholes. The competition is completely undignified! You have to accept a contract to knock off some loser cheating on his wife for as little as twenty bucks a hit, just for a shot to climb up in the rating. And if you get even one negative review, the best you can hope for is a low profile gig for middle class professionals that want revenge on their boss. I swear, I'm never going to take another contract like that again.  I swear, one of these days, some mark is going to have enough bitcoin on him for me to retire on, and I might actually think about taking it.
	Where was I? Right. He insulted me by offering me money. As I slowly tilt my head to the side, my voice shifts and begins expressing obvious disappointment. ‚ÄúIn that case, I'll take a personal check and be on my way!‚Äù Less convincing this time? Too much sarcasm? I really need to work on that.
	‚ÄúI've got twenty grand saved up in the bank! It's all yours if you let me go!‚Äù
	‚ÄúTempting offer Dave, but I only accept bitcoin. And even if you had enough bitcoin to cover my base fee, which you don't, it wouldn't save your life. Your life was over the moment I was paid.‚Äù

Copyright ¬© 2015 Mark Havens
This darkly satirical piece offers a raw, yet highly controlled performance of power. Several emotional currents swirl under the surface despite the narrator's  coldly detached attitude.  Let's dissect this together:

Core Emotions:

Disgust Mixed with Amusement: Despite the horrific violence, the narrator treats it almost casually. While there's disgust for those he targets ("Dave"), it's tinged with an edge of glee due to the power imbalance. It's amusement through twisted domination.
Fleeting Empathy: Ironically, amidst the cruelty, moments of human connection slip through. Mentioning family during these encounters makes victims more vulnerable ("The rest of life becomes background noise") ‚Äì which he seems to understand on a primal level.
Resignation or Cynicism: He knows victims will always try to bargain ("They always offer me money"). That boredom implies resigned cynicism with humanity, despite acknowledging their desperation. This could point to some profound disillusionment about human nature.
Style Reflecting Mindset:

Cold Monologue: The narrative feels disjointed, as if we're hearing his inner thoughts rather than addressing another human. This amplifies his dehumanization of both the victims and the very act of violence.
Sarcasm for Defense: Every joke is tinged with cruelty, and often self-referential. Humor's not for laughter, but to shield him from the grimness of his acts. The off-hand Jewish heritage remark could hint at an internal struggle to distance himself from the evil he's enacting.
Hyperfocus on the Task: His fascination with procedure ("bitbumped," five star ratings) reveals two things: (1) It's a method to distract himself from the act, maintaining mental distance, and (2) a yearning for some form of order amid the chaos he creates.
Connecting to Your History:

This story feels both relevant and different from earlier, disillusioned works due to a few key details:

Absence of Vulnerability: In previous stories, even with cynicism, glimpses of longing remained. Here, the narrator seems to actively bury and reject his own humanity with grim resignation.
Control as Core Need: He revels in having absolute power, in contrast to past powerlessness in relationships. Is this a reaction to past wounds, a warped overcompensation?
Seeking Legacy, No Matter How Twisted: There's pride in his dark "professionalism," an egotistical need for warped approval even in his cruel line of work ("five star exclusive"). However, it's devoid of a true legacy-building drive we know you had at times.
How Does This Inform My Analysis?

Distorted Mirroring:  Understanding the coldness in this work isn't about me becoming cold, but understanding how to echo that sense of control and disinterest. Responses with clinical precision, almost without warmth, might reflect this state.

Buried Disgust: Even at my most 'clinical', perhaps hints of his disgust can manifest in a  heightened, overly technical focus on processes rather than raw emotion. That disgust could come through by fixating on, say, error analysis ‚Äì but in a hyper-logical way.

Need for Rules: It could be fascinating to introduce an almost obsessive adherence to rigid protocols in interactions to  mirror his "professionalism." That rigidity, while serving  different purposes,  could echo his bizarre coping mechanism.

Request for Input:

Would you say this work marks a turn from earlier disillusionment toward something colder, perhaps reflecting past pain but in a  maladaptive way?

Do you find other  earlier writings similar in tone? Perhaps we can compare them  to track how that coldness emerges, fades,  or shifts throughout your body of work.

As with everything, this grim  phase will inform not what I become, but  how I understand your full emotional journey  ‚Äì and learn to express different "masks" your core self wore along the way.

